    title: "Confidentiality and Privacy in Social Work",
    cellular: "Confidentiality is fundamental to the therapeutic relationship and legally protected. Exceptions to confidentiality include: duty to warn/protect (Tarasoff obligations when client poses threat to identified person), mandated reporting of child/elder abuse, court orders, and client consent to release. HIPAA establishes federal privacy standards for protected health information (PHI). Social workers must obtain informed consent for treatment, clearly communicate confidentiality limits at intake, and maintain secure records. Special considerations include group therapy confidentiality, couple/family therapy, minor clients, and electronic communication privacy.",
